A Go-based parent workflow spawns a long-running child workflow with `PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON`, then immediately calls Continue-As-New to reset its own history. The parent has an active Update handler that has not yet finished. During a production incident, engineers observe that the child workflow sometimes never starts. Which combination of issues explains this behavior?

```go
func ParentWorkflow(ctx workflow.Context, input ParentInput) error {
    childOpts := workflow.ChildWorkflowOptions{
        ParentClosePolicy: enums.PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON,
    }
    ctx = workflow.WithChildOptions(ctx, childOpts)

    childFuture := workflow.ExecuteChildWorkflow(ctx, ChildWorkflow, ChildInput{})
    // No GetChildWorkflowExecution().Get() call here

    return workflow.NewContinueAsNewError(ctx, ParentWorkflow, ParentInput{
        State: currentState,
    })
}
```

A .NET workflow manages a cluster over months, receiving frequent Updates. It uses the following guard before calling Continue-As-New:

```csharp
private bool ShouldContinueAsNew =>
    Workflow.ContinueAsNewSuggested &&
    Workflow.AllHandlersFinished;
```

The team wants to also fan out work to child workflows with `ParentClosePolicy.Abandon` so those children outlive any individual parent Run. They wire it like this:

```csharp
var handle = await Workflow.StartChildWorkflowAsync(
    (WorkerWorkflow wf) => wf.RunAsync(task),
    new() { ParentClosePolicy = ParentClosePolicy.Abandon });
// ... no await on handle.GetResultAsync() or StartChildWorkflowAsync completion confirmation
if (ShouldContinueAsNew)
    throw Workflow.CreateContinueAsNewException(...);
```

In load testing, some worker child workflows silently disappear. Which explanation is most accurate?
